'{"corrected_text":"[LAW.] SUPREME COURT.-FRIDAY. NEW TRIAL OF CAUSES. HIGH COURT. -Justice Dickinson and a jury of four. CASE OF HART V. MONROE. The claim of ejectment to recover possession of lots at Paddington, of which the plaintiff was the owner, was cleared for the plaintiff, and Mr. T. Sheahan defended. Plaintiff was an elderly female named Barbara Hart, and her grounds of action were very strange. After having formerly lived for some six months with the defendant, Daniel Francis Monroe, at Hawkesbury, plaintiff had executed a conveyance of the property in question, in consideration of £200, and agreeing to provide her with good and sufficient board, lodging, and washing, for the rest of her life." In this shape the deed was signed and sealed, but at the foot of it there was a memorandum of defeasance also executed by Monroe, to the effect that if he failed at any time to execute his part of the contract Mrs. Hart might re-enter. The plaintiff\'s mode was, that she had been improperly lodged and fed, but upon this point the evidence was conflicting. There was, however, a question of law as well as of fact in reference to the memorandum of defeasance at the foot of the deed, which has already been referred to. This was whether the memorandum had been executed prior to the delivery. Upon this point the evidence was not very distinct, but it would appear that after the execution of the conveyance, and before handing it over to Monroe, the conveyancer, the memorandum was added for both parties, and procured Monroe\'s signature by way of rendering Mrs. Hart\'s position more secure. There was a great deal of conflicting evidence as to the habits and mode of living, too, of the parties concerned, which need not be here entered.","has_modifications":true}'
